05028nam a2200733Ia 9780801462443DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014624437 a10.7591/97808014624432doi  a(DE-B1597)515342  a(OCoLC)1083588267  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD2856b.T53 2007eb 7aPOL0230002bisacsh04a338.62221 aTiberghien, Yves, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEntrepreneurial States :bReforming Corporate Governance in France, Japan, and Korea /cYves Tiberghien. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b16 tables, 4 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Political Economy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Political Entrepreneurs and the Corporate Restructuring Dilemma -- t2. A Story of Change and Divergence -- t3. France: Effective but "Shameful" Reforms -- t4. Japan: Of Change and Resistance -- t5. Korea: Systemic Transformation -- t6. Political Entrepreneurs and the Great Transformation of the Automobile Industry -- tConclusion: From Social Contract to Golden Bargain? -- tAppendix: Evaluation of Corporate Reform Intensity in France, Japan, Korea, and Germany -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Entrepreneurial States, an innovative examination of the comparative politics of reform in stakeholder systems, Yves Tiberghien analyzes the modern partnership between the state and global capital in attaining structural domestic change. The emergence of a powerful global equity market has altered incentives for the state and presented political leaders with a "golden bargain"—the infusion of abundant and cheap capital into domestic stock markets in exchange for reform of corporate governance and other regulatory changes.Drawing on extensive archival research and interviews with policy and corporate elites in Europe and East Asia, Tiberghien asks why states such as Korea and France have embraced this opportunity and engaged in far-reaching reforms to make their companies more attractive to foreign capital, whereas Japan and Germany have moved forward much more grudgingly. Interest groups and electoral institutions have their impacts, but by tracing the unfolding dynamic of reform under different constraints, Tiberghien shows that the role of political entrepreneurs is critical. Such policy elites act as mediators between global forces and national constraints. As risk takers and bargain builders, Tiberghien finds, they use corporate reform to reshape their political parties and to stake out new policy ground. The degree of political autonomy available to them and the domestic organization of bureaucratic responsibility determine their ability to succeed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCapital movementsxGovernment policyzFrance. 0aCapital movementsxGovernment policyzJapan. 0aCapital movementsxGovernment policyzKorea (South). 0aCorporate governancexPolitical aspectszFrance. 0aCorporate governancexPolitical aspectszJapan. 0aCorporate governancexPolitical aspectszKorea (South). 0aCorporate reorganizationsxPolitical aspectszFrance. 0aCorporate reorganizationsxPolitical aspectszJapan. 0aCorporate reorganizationsxPolitical aspectszKorea (South). 4aGeneral Economics. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146244340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801462443423Cover